        content: "An **Applicant Tracking System (ATS)** is software that scans, sorts, and ranks job applications before human recruiters see them.\n\n### How ATS Works\n\n1. **Parsing** – ATS extracts text from your resume\n2. **Keyword Matching** – Compares your content to job requirements\n3. **Scoring** – Assigns a match percentage\n4. **Filtering** – Low-scoring resumes never reach humans\n\n### 2026 ATS Statistics\n\n| Statistic | Impact |\n|-----------|--------|\n| Companies using ATS | 98% of Fortune 500, 66% of mid-size |\n| Resumes rejected by ATS | 75% before human review |\n| Time to scan a resume | 6 seconds average |\n| Resumes never seen by humans | 70% at large companies |\n\n### Popular ATS Systems\n\n- **Workday** – Used by Amazon, Target, many Fortune 500\n- **Taleo** – Oracle's system, common in enterprise\n- **Greenhouse** – Popular with tech and startups\n- **iCIMS** – Used in hospitality and retail\n- **Lever** – Growing in mid-size companies\n\n> **Key Insight:** If your resume isn't ATS-optimized, you could be qualified for a job and never even be considered because the software filtered you out."
